rimary focus of this book is on metaphysical issues concerning the nature of death: What is the nature of the harm or bad involved in death? (If it is not pain, wha is it, and how can it be bad?) Who is the subject of the harm or bad? (if the person is no longer alive, how can he be the subject of the bad? An if he is not the subject, who is? Can one have harm with no subject?) When does the harm take place? (Can a harm take place after its subject ceases to exist? If death harms a person, can the harm take place before the death occurs?) If death can be a bad thing, would immorality be a desirable alternative? This family of questions helps to fram ethe puzzle of why—and how—death is bad. Other subjects addressed include the Epicurean view othat death is not a misfortune (for the person who dies); the nature of misfortune and benefit; the meaningulness and value of life; and the distinction between the life of a person and the life of a living creature who is not a person. There is an extensive bibiography that includes science-fiction treatments of death and immorality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Humanism.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Woody, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrueckner, Anthony L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeinberg, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeldman, Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, John Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, John Martin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLuper-Foy, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcMahan, Jeff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary